# Essential to know
- `display`: `block`, `inline`, `inline-block`, `none`, `flex`, `grid`
- `position`: `static`, `relative`, `absolute`, `fixed`, `sticky`
- `relative` + `absolute` combo for positioning children
- `z-index` controls stacking order

---

# Display & Position

Understanding display and position properties is fundamental to controlling how elements appear and relate to each other on the page.

## Display Property

The display property determines how an element generates boxes and interacts with other elements.

### Block
Block elements take up the full width available and create new lines:

```css
.block {
  display: block;  /* Default for div, p, h1-h6, section */
  width: 100%;     /* Full width by default */
}
```

**Block characteristics:**
- Always starts on a new line
- Takes full width available
- Respects width/height, margin, padding
- Examples: `div`, `p`, `h1`, `section`, `article`

### Inline
Inline elements flow within text and don't break the line:

```css
.inline {
  display: inline;  /* Default for span, a, strong, em */
}
```

**Inline characteristics:**
- Doesn't start on a new line
- Only takes as much width as needed
- Ignores width/height properties
- Only horizontal margins/padding work
- Examples: `span`, `a`, `strong`, `em`, `code`

### Inline-Block
Best of both worlds - flows like inline but respects box model like block:

```css
.inline-block {
  display: inline-block;
  width: 100px;
  height: 50px;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 5px;
}
```

**Use cases:**
- Navigation links
- Buttons in a row
- Cards in horizontal scroll
- Badges/tags

```html
<nav>
  <a href="/" class="nav-link">Home</a>
  <a href="/about" class="nav-link">About</a>
  <a href="/contact" class="nav-link">Contact</a>
</nav>
```

```css
.nav-link {
  display: inline-block;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  margin-right: 10px;
}
```

### None
Completely removes element from layout:

```css
.hidden {
  display: none;
}
```

**Note:** Use `visibility: hidden` if you want to hide but preserve space.

## Position Property

Positioning allows you to move elements outside the normal document flow.

### Static (Default)
Normal document flow:

```css
.normal {
  position: static;  /* Default */
}
```

### Relative
Positioned relative to its normal position:

```css
.relative {
  position: relative;
  top: 10px;      /* Move down 10px */
  left: 20px;     /* Move right 20px */
  /* Original space is preserved */
}
```

**Key points:**
- Element stays in document flow
- Creates positioning context for absolute children
- Other elements don't fill its original space

### Absolute
Positioned relative to nearest positioned ancestor:

```css
.parent {
  position: relative;  /* Creates positioning context */
}

.child {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
  /* Removed from document flow */
}
```

**Common use cases:**

1. **Notification Badge**
```css
.cart-button {
  position: relative;
}

.badge {
  position: absolute;
  top: -8px;
  right: -8px;
  background: red;
  color: white;
  padding: 2px 6px;
  border-radius: 50%;
}
```

2. **Dropdown Menu**
```css
.dropdown {
  position: relative;
}

.dropdown-menu {
  position: absolute;
  top: 100%;      /* Below the trigger */
  left: 0;
  width: 200px;
  /* Hidden by default, shown on hover/click */
}
```

3. **Modal Overlay**
```css
.modal-overlay {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
}
```

### Fixed
Positioned relative to viewport, stays in place on scroll:

```css
.navbar {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  z-index: 100;
}

.back-to-top {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 20px;
  right: 20px;
}
```

**Use cases:**
- Fixed navigation bars
- Sticky ads
- Back-to-top buttons
- Chat widgets

### Sticky
Hybrid between relative and fixed:

```css
.sticky-header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;  /* Sticks when scrolled to top: 0 */
}
```

**How it works:**
- Acts like `position: relative` initially
- Becomes `position: fixed` when scroll reaches threshold
- Stays within parent container

**Use cases:**
- Table headers that stick while scrolling
- Section headers in long articles
- Sidebar navigation

```css
.table-container {
  max-height: 400px;
  overflow: auto;
}

.table-header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  background: white;
  z-index: 10;
}
```

## Z-Index

Controls stacking order of positioned elements:

```css
.modal {
  position: fixed;
  z-index: 1000;  /* On top */
}

.overlay {
  position: fixed;
  z-index: 999;
}

.navbar {
  position: sticky;
  z-index: 100;
}
```

**Important:**
- Only works on positioned elements (not static)
- Higher number = on top
- Creates stacking context
- Children can't escape parent's z-index

## Common Patterns

### Centering with Absolute Positioning
```css
.parent {
  position: relative;
}

.centered {
  position: absolute;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
}
```

### Full-Coverage Overlay
```css
.overlay {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
}
```

### Aspect Ratio Box
```css
.aspect-ratio-box {
  position: relative;
  width: 100%;
  padding-top: 56.25%;  /* 16:9 aspect ratio */
}

.aspect-ratio-box > * {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
}
```

## Quick Reference

```css
/* Display */
.block { display: block; }
.inline { display: inline; }
.inline-block { display: inline-block; }
.hidden { display: none; }

/* Positioning context */
.relative { position: relative; }
.absolute { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; }
.fixed { position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; }
.sticky { position: sticky; top: 0; }

/* Centering */
.center {
  position: absolute;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
}
```

**Remember:**
- ✅ Use `position: relative` to create positioning context
- ✅ Use `position: absolute` for overlays, badges, dropdowns
- ✅ Use `position: fixed` for navbars and floating buttons
- ✅ Use `position: sticky` for headers that stick while scrolling
- ✅ Use `z-index` to control stacking order
- ❌ Don't use absolute positioning for main layout
- ❌ Don't forget to set positioning context for absolute children

# Essential to know
- `display: flex` on parent makes children flex items
- `justify-content` for main axis alignment
- `align-items` for cross axis alignment
- `flex-direction`: `row` (default) or `column`
- `gap` adds space between items

---

# Flexbox

Flexbox (Flexible Box Layout) is a one-dimensional layout method for arranging items in rows or columns. It's perfect for navigation bars, card layouts, centering, and distributing space.

## Getting Started

To create a flex container, set `display: flex` on the parent:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
}
```

This turns all direct children into **flex items** that align horizontally by default.

## Main Concepts

### Flex Direction
Controls the main axis direction:

```css
.row {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;  /* Default: left to right */
}

.column {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;  /* Top to bottom */
}

.row-reverse {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row-reverse;  /* Right to left */
}
```

### Justify Content (Main Axis)
Aligns items along the main axis (horizontal for row, vertical for column):

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-start;    /* Default */
  justify-content: flex-end;      /* Right/bottom aligned */
  justify-content: center;        /* Centered */
  justify-content: space-between; /* Space between items */
  justify-content: space-around;  /* Space around items */
  justify-content: space-evenly;  /* Equal space */
}
```

**Visual examples:**

```
flex-start:    [A][B][C]                        
flex-end:                         [A][B][C]    
center:              [A][B][C]                   
space-between: [A]        [B]        [C]        
space-around:  [ A ]    [ B ]    [ C ]         
space-evenly:  [  A  ][  B  ][  C  ]           
```

### Align Items (Cross Axis)
Aligns items along the cross axis (perpendicular to main axis):

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  align-items: stretch;     /* Default: fill container */
  align-items: flex-start;  /* Top/left aligned */
  align-items: flex-end;    /* Bottom/right aligned */
  align-items: center;      /* Centered */
  align-items: baseline;    /* Text baseline aligned */
}
```

### Perfect Centering
The classic flexbox use case:

```css
.center-container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;  /* Horizontal center */
  align-items: center;      /* Vertical center */
  min-height: 100vh;        /* Full viewport height */
}
```

## Flex Properties

### Gap
Adds space between flex items (modern replacement for margins):

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  gap: 16px;          /* Both directions */
  gap: 16px 24px;     /* Row gap, column gap */
  row-gap: 16px;      /* Just row */
  column-gap: 24px;   /* Just column */
}
```

### Flex Wrap
Allow items to wrap to next line:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;    /* Items wrap */
  gap: 16px;
}

.item {
  flex: 1 1 300px;    /* Grow, shrink, basis */
}
```

### Flex (Shorthand)
Controls how items grow and shrink:

```css
.item {
  /* flex: grow shrink basis */
  flex: 1;              /* flex: 1 1 0% */
  flex: 0 0 200px;      /* Fixed 200px, no grow/shrink */
  flex: 1 1 auto;       /* Grow and shrink from content size */
}
```

**Examples:**

```css
/* Equal width columns */
.column {
  flex: 1;  /* All columns same width */
}

/* Sidebar + Main content */
.sidebar {
  flex: 0 0 250px;  /* Fixed 250px */
}

.main {
  flex: 1;  /* Takes remaining space */
}
```

## Common Layout Patterns

### Navigation Bar
```css
.navbar {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;  /* Logo left, nav right */
  align-items: center;
  padding: 1rem 2rem;
}

.nav-links {
  display: flex;
  gap: 2rem;
}
```

### Card Layout
```css
.card-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 1.5rem;
}

.card {
  flex: 1 1 300px;  /* At least 300px, grow equally */
}
```

### Holy Grail Layout
```css
.layout {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  min-height: 100vh;
}

.main {
  display: flex;
  flex: 1;
}

.sidebar {
  flex: 0 0 200px;
}

.content {
  flex: 1;
}
```

### Vertical Stack
```css
.stack {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 1rem;
}

.stack > * {
  margin-top: 0;
  margin-bottom: 0;
}
```

## Individual Item Alignment

Override alignment for specific items:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
}

.tall-item {
  align-self: stretch;  /* Fill container height */
}

.top-item {
  align-self: flex-start;
}
```

## Quick Reference

```css
/* Container */
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row | column;
  flex-wrap: wrap | nowrap;
  justify-content: flex-start | center | space-between | space-around;
  align-items: stretch | flex-start | center | flex-end;
  align-content: stretch | flex-start | center;  /* Multi-line */
  gap: 16px;
}

/* Items */
.item {
  flex: 1;              /* Grow equally */
  flex: 0 0 200px;      /* Fixed width */
  order: 2;             /* Visual order (default 0) */
  align-self: center;   /* Override container alignment */
}
```

**Remember:**
- ✅ Use flexbox for one-dimensional layouts (row OR column)
- ✅ Use `gap` instead of margins between items
- ✅ Use `flex: 1` for equal-width columns
- ✅ Use `justify-content: center` + `align-items: center` for perfect centering
- ✅ Set `flex-wrap: wrap` for responsive layouts
- ❌ Don't use flexbox for complex two-dimensional grids (use CSS Grid)
- ❌ Don't forget `align-items` defaults to `stretch`

# Essential to know
- `display: grid` creates a grid container
- `grid-template-columns` defines columns
- `fr` unit: fraction of available space
- `gap` for gutters between cells
- `grid-column: span 2` for spanning

---

# CSS Grid

CSS Grid is a two-dimensional layout system that handles both rows and columns simultaneously. It's the most powerful layout tool in CSS.

## Getting Started

Create a grid container:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
}
```

## Defining Grid Structure

### Grid Template Columns
Define column sizes:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;

  /* Fixed width columns */
  grid-template-columns: 200px 200px 200px;

  /* Fluid columns with fr unit */
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;

  /* Mixed */
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr 2fr;  /* Fixed, 1 part, 2 parts */
}
```

### The fr Unit
Fraction of available space (like flex-grow):

```css
.container {
  display: grid;

  /* Three equal columns */
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;

  /* Sidebar + Main content */
  grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr;

  /* Three columns: 1/6, 2/6, 3/6 */
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 3fr;
}
```

### Repeat Function
For repetitive patterns:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;

  /* 3 columns, each 1fr */
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);

  /* 4 columns: 100px, 1fr, 100px, 1fr */
  grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 100px 1fr);

  /* 12-column grid */
  grid-template-columns: repeat(12, 1fr);
}
```

### Minmax Function
Set minimum and maximum sizes:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;

  /* At least 200px, at most 1fr */
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(200px, 1fr));

  /* Responsive without media queries */
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
}
```

## Grid Template Rows

Similar to columns but for height:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  grid-template-rows: 100px 1fr 100px;  /* Header, content, footer */
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```

## Gap (Gutter)

Space between grid cells:

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 20px;           /* Both row and column */
  gap: 20px 10px;      /* Row gap, column gap */
  row-gap: 20px;       /* Just rows */
  column-gap: 10px;    /* Just columns */
}
```

## Placing Items

### Grid Column/Row (Shorthand)
```css
.item-wide {
  grid-column: span 2;  /* Span 2 columns */
}

.item-tall {
  grid-row: span 2;     /* Span 2 rows */
}

.item-specific {
  /* Start at line 1, end at line 3 */
  grid-column: 1 / 3;
  grid-row: 2 / 4;
}
```

### Grid Area
```css
.header { grid-area: header; }
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.main { grid-area: main; }
.footer { grid-area: footer; }

.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  grid-template-areas:
    "header header"
    "sidebar main"
    "footer footer";
  gap: 20px;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```

## Common Layout Patterns

### Photo Gallery
```css
.gallery {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
  gap: 16px;
}

.gallery img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 200px;
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

### Dashboard Layout
```css
.dashboard {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr;
  grid-template-rows: 60px 1fr;
  grid-template-areas:
    "sidebar header"
    "sidebar main";
  min-height: 100vh;
}

.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.header { grid-area: header; }
.main { grid-area: main; }
```

### Magazine Layout
```css
.magazine {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
  gap: 20px;
}

.featured {
  grid-column: span 2;
  grid-row: span 2;
}

.ad {
  grid-column: span 2;
}
```

### Responsive Grid (No Media Queries)
```css
.auto-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
  gap: 24px;
}
```

This creates as many columns as fit, each at least 300px wide.

## Grid vs Flexbox

| Grid | Flexbox |
|------|---------|
| Two-dimensional (rows + columns) | One-dimensional (row OR column) |
| Layout-first (define structure) | Content-first (items dictate size) |
| Gap works in both directions | Gap works in flex direction only |
| Better for page layouts | Better for component layouts |
| Can overlap items easily | Overlap requires positioning |

**When to use Grid:**
- Page layouts (header, sidebar, main, footer)
- Card galleries
- Dashboard layouts
- Magazine-style layouts

**When to use Flexbox:**
- Navigation bars
- Form alignments
- Centering single elements
- Button groups

## Quick Reference

```css
/* Container */
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  gap: 20px;
}

/* Common patterns */
.two-columns { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
.sidebar-layout { grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr; }
.auto-responsive { grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr)); }

/* Items */
.item {
  grid-column: span 2;
  grid-row: 1 / 3;
}
```

**Remember:**
- ✅ Use Grid for two-dimensional layouts
- ✅ Use `repeat()` for repetitive patterns
- ✅ Use `fr` for flexible sizing
- ✅ Use `minmax()` for responsive grids without media queries
- ✅ Use `grid-template-areas` for named layouts
- ❌ Don't use Grid when Flexbox is simpler
- ❌ Don't forget `gap` for spacing (better than margins)

# Essential to know
- Media queries: `@media (min-width: 768px) {}`
- Mobile-first: start with small screens, add breakpoints
- `max-width` prevents content from stretching too wide
- `min-width` breakpoints: 640px (sm), 768px (md), 1024px (lg)

---

# Responsive Design

Responsive design ensures your website looks good on all devices - from mobile phones to desktop monitors.

## Mobile-First Approach

Start with the smallest screen and progressively enhance for larger screens:

```css
/* Mobile styles (default) */
.container {
  padding: 1rem;
}

/* Tablet */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    padding: 2rem;
  }
}

/* Desktop */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    padding: 3rem;
  }
}
```

**Why mobile-first?**
- Mobile traffic often exceeds desktop
- Forces you to prioritize content
- CSS is simpler (fewer overrides)
- Better performance on mobile

## Media Queries

### Basic Syntax
```css
@media (condition) {
  /* Styles apply when condition is true */
}
```

### Common Breakpoints
```css
/* Small devices (phones) */
@media (min-width: 640px) { }  /* sm */

/* Medium devices (tablets) */
@media (min-width: 768px) { }  /* md */

/* Large devices (laptops) */
@media (min-width: 1024px) { } /* lg */

/* Extra large (desktops) */
@media (min-width: 1280px) { } /* xl */
```

### Common Conditions
```css
/* Width-based */
@media (min-width: 768px) { }  /* 768px and up */
@media (max-width: 767px) { }  /* 767px and down */
@media (min-width: 768px) and (max-width: 1023px) { }  /* Range */

/* Height-based */
@media (min-height: 600px) { }

/* Orientation */
@media (orientation: landscape) { }
@media (orientation: portrait) { }

/* Dark mode */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  body {
    background: #1a1a1a;
    color: #ffffff;
  }
}

/* Reduced motion preference */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  * {
    animation: none !important;
    transition: none !important;
  }
}
```

## Responsive Patterns

### Fluid Typography
```css
html {
  font-size: 16px;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  html {
    font-size: 18px;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1280px) {
  html {
    font-size: 20px;
  }
}

/* All rem values scale automatically */
h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; }  /* 40px → 45px → 50px */
```

### Responsive Grid
```css
.grid {
  display: grid;
  gap: 1rem;

  /* Mobile: 1 column */
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
}

@media (min-width: 640px) {
  .grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1280px) {
  .grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
  }
}
```

### Responsive Navigation
```css
/* Mobile: Hamburger menu (hidden by default) */
.nav-links {
  display: none;
}

.nav-links.open {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
}

/* Desktop: Horizontal nav */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;
    gap: 2rem;
  }

  .hamburger {
    display: none;
  }
}
```

### Container with Max-Width
```css
.container {
  width: 90%;
  max-width: 1200px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 0 1rem;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    padding: 0 2rem;
  }
}
```

### Responsive Images
```css
img {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}

/* Or for full-width */
.responsive-image {
  width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}
```

## Viewport Meta Tag

Essential for responsive design on mobile:

```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
```

**What it does:**
- `width=device-width`: Sets width to device screen width
- `initial-scale=1.0`: Sets initial zoom level to 1

Without this, mobile browsers will zoom out to show desktop layouts.

## Responsive Units

### Relative Units
```css
/* Percentages - relative to parent */
width: 50%;

/* Viewport units */
width: 100vw;        /* Full viewport width */
height: 100vh;       /* Full viewport height */
font-size: 5vw;      /* Scales with viewport */

/* clamp() - responsive with limits */
font-size: clamp(1rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);  /* Min, Preferred, Max */
```

### When to Use What
- **rem/em**: Font sizes, spacing (accessible)
- **%**: Widths, fluid layouts
- **vw/vh**: Full-viewport sections
- **px**: Borders, small details
- **clamp()**: Fluid typography

## Common Responsive Mistakes

### ❌ Fixed Widths Everywhere
```css
/* Bad */
.container { width: 1200px; }  /* Breaks on mobile */

/* Good */
.container {
  width: 90%;
  max-width: 1200px;
}
```

### ❌ Too Many Breakpoints
```css
/* Overly complex */
@media (min-width: 320px) { }
@media (min-width: 375px) { }
@media (min-width: 414px) { }
/* ... too many! */

/* Simpler */
@media (min-width: 640px) { }
@media (min-width: 768px) { }
@media (min-width: 1024px) { }
```

### ❌ Desktop-First Media Queries
```css
/* Desktop-first (harder to maintain) */
.container { width: 1200px; }

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .container { width: 100%; }
}

/* Mobile-first (better) */
.container { width: 100%; }

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container { width: 1200px; }
}
```

## Testing Responsive Design

1. **Browser DevTools**
   - Toggle device toolbar
   - Test different screen sizes
   - Test touch vs mouse

2. **Actual Devices**
   - Test on real phones/tablets
   - Different browsers (Safari, Chrome)
   - Different orientations

3. **Online Tools**
